            "answer_text": "Indian-American view. I am not the most familiar with Indian music culture, but this is from what I've gathered. Also, I have redone my answer to fit more in line with K-Pop.____________________Westernization Since this is rather self explanatory...I'll keep it short. Westernized beats, melodies, and singing styles. Many songs are sounding more and more western now, so that's good. Though many songs stay un-westernized (which is not a bad thing...I love regular Indian music as well.) Westernized music just sounds more familiar to me, haha. DiversityThere is not much diversity when it comes to Indian music. I think this is due to the fact the majority of Indian music comes from movies and are often involved with love scenes/fantasy scenes. these fantasy scenes lead on to my next point... \"Pop\"! (Most Important)You said as popular as K-Pop. And there isn't much \"Pop\"! when it comes to Indian musican. And by that I mean...as beautiful as Indian songs are, they just are not pop songs. They don't have that catchy beat that infects you and makes you hum it on a loop for days on end. So even without the language barriers it would be targeting a specific audience.With K-Pop they have the pop part down so hard, everything about the sound of their music is catchy, fun to dance to, and down right infectious. So even though it's in Korean you can have fun. (This is also seen with French artist Stromae for his more popular songs) The Artist & The FansBecause most music is created for the film industry (Bolly, Tolly, Kolly...etc) the singers are not up front, it's just fantasy sequence after fantasy sequence. While this is great for a movie it is not great for a musician. A musician has to be up front in center in most cases, there has to be some sort of relationship between artist and fans. If all the singers are are behind the scenes, the actors get all the attention. Producers seem to be a bigger deal in India rather than singers. If you look at K-Pop they have a great relationship with their fans, often on television, music videos, so many gifssss SO MANY! Bi-LingualMany K-Pop songs incorporate English. But it is always more than a few words scattered about...perhaps a whole bridge. And they also work to not have a strong Korean accent during those parts. Just a little dash of it for flavor~ Also, English add-libs. VideosK-Pop videos have a certain style, this is evident in every video. Very art-based and that's their thing. Lot of influences from things in their culture. But also a lot of westernized stuff...dancing...themes...outfits(well K-pop fashion, but I hope you get what I mean)...etc. India has to do the same, it doesn't have to be fashion centered like K-Pop, but it has to find its thing and mix it with westernized stuff. This doesn't mean completely ripping off old/new western stuff. (I saw this very awkward video where this girl was trying to imitate Britney spears in this Telugu video...just...no.) If it's just a copy it won't wow anyone, it has to be a new style that can appeal to both audiences in India and in the global market. Lyrics?While I believe lyrics and their meaning are important (I personally cannot listen to many songs without lyrics except for classical) I disagree with Alvika on the fact that the lyrics have to make complete sense. It wouldn't hurt, for sure. But music does not need a specific language to communicate. That being said, I really hope to see Telugu and other Indian music make it big. I think what would be great is if more Indian-Americans made music in their second language...the best of both worlds thing going on and trying mixing it together. Also...Searching for acoustic covers can sometimes lead to some fun results. Like this artist. And I know these are not pop songs, but I think they're a bit westernized and can help people who can't look past the unique style of regular Indian music do exactly that. (All Telugu songs, also an Italian song to compare to, it's kinda poppy, but not really, just westernized.)    And some Italiano:  ",
